Back home—anywhere in the mountains clicked into a pair of skis, that is. The past couple days exemplified what it’s all about for me: Connecting with good friends through deep conversation on the skintrack, feeling child-like joy while harvesting powder, and soaking in the positive energy of being high in the mountains. ⁣
 ⁣
It’s been a weird start to the ski season for me personally with how much I was on the road and on tour non-stop all fall. I’m still not sure where home is more than the skintrack, and I think I’m going to give up on trying to label home geographically for a while. But this week I’m sleeping in one bed for the longest stretch since running Leadville. I’m on my skis again with high-level human beings. And I sure do love it here geographically. And all of that feels really, really freaking good. And that’s enough for right now. ⁣
 ⁣

Overdue on this post, but… Woo! That’s a wrap on the 2022 Quality Ski Time Film Tour. This fall was wild. I was on tour for 17 events. And all that I have to say boils down to thank you to each and every one of you who came out to a show. 
 
Two years deep on this tour, and it feels like what @salomonfreeski and I hoped it would become when we started it together: an opportunity to gather the community and celebrate our shared passion of sliding down snow. It’s a simple goal, but it means a lot to get to make that gathering and connection happen in-person with laughs, hugs, and high-fives rather than just digitally with empty likes and scrolling—like most of our world is nowadays. Selfishly, I love getting to meet so many passionate skiers and hearing your stories, where you ski, and what you’re psyched on for the winter ahead.
 
From having to throw down an unplanned standup show on the mic all the way to my middle school science teacher winning the skis at my hometown show (not rigged, I swear), this year was a full-value experience. Mixed in there were creemees in Vermont, running back on the interstate to pick up a raffle prize that flew out of the truck, midnight soulo Bird scooter joy rides in sketchy parts of cities, getting dressed pre-show in back alleys, and signing 550 posters for 550 really awesome human beings.
 
So yeah, just like you’ve heard me say like a broken record if you’ve come to an event, thanks for coming. Thanks for the support. Thanks for sharing your stoke and passion and love for skiing. 
 
And now, let it snow. Ski and enjoy, my friends. 🤙❄️

One of my favorite parts of the film tour is experiencing so many different places through running. My preferred modus operandi is to lace up my shoes with no plan or route and just go see what I find. I enjoy the freedom to turn onto neat-looking roads or run toward buildings and attractions that intrigue me. 

Some spots I got to run trails with friends. But of course, many of these locales were big cities, where normally I’d be a fish out of water. But I think I’ve developed a love for how foreign it feels and how quickly I can connect with a place in this manner. And yes, I even convinced myself to enjoy running on pavement. 

My fitness pretty much went to trash from so much travel and work, but c’est la vie. I’m hopefully learning how to find some better balance for the future. But this wasn’t about training. Sometimes it’s good to put aside the heart rate monitor, get reconnected with my body, and just go run purely for fun and to experience a place for what it is. 

A few of the highlights, somewhat, but not totally, in order of the photos:
- I *get* why Central Park in NYC is so cool now. 
- Running along the Charles in Boston with a pit stop to solve equations on a chalk board at MIT.
- Old history in Boston—like George Washington statues and cemeteries where the founding fathers are buried. 
- Fall across the West was primo this year.
- Running through the Seattle Mariners playoff atmosphere. Seattle might be my favorite city to run in. 
- Portland is an interestingly weird city. In a lot of ways. 
- Getting back home to Tahoe in between shows. 
- I *literally* run on Dunkin’ on the East Coast.

I typically haven’t been sharing much of this side of my life. Through 2022, I’ve been working on starting a public speaking career. Some of the gigs I’ve mentioned on here. Some I haven’t. 

I’ve been everywhere from ski resorts and high schools to a wildland firefighting base. Geographically though, it’s mostly been around mountains—whether West coast or East coast. So that made this one a couple-few weeks ago—in Clearwater, Florida—especially unique. 

@love_iv_lawrence brought me in to speak at their fundraiser, Reeling in Stigma, alongside @bguyer5, a MLB player turned mental performance coach and Brooke Bennett, a three-time Olympic Gold Medalist swimmer. 

It’s not a circle I’m used to brushing shoulders in. So I just spoke from my heart. Because my story isn’t about being a skier and it’s not encapsulated by the suicide epidemic of our mountain communities. My story is simply about being human. Even still, I’m constantly floored by how deeply and widely my story resonates. 

Thanks to @love_iv_lawrence for bringing me down. The way this group of humans has channeled their grief felt from the loss of their son, brother, and friend into a mission for a better future is inspiring beyond words. Thank you for welcoming me into your community. My heart will always hold a special place for all of you. 

——

Just like the Hallmark channel, there’s more where Hallmark of a Ski Bum came from. Subscribe now so you don’t miss a single ski town holiday rom-com flick that may or may not be inspired by real life events.

Thanks to @sundayriver for elevating the conversation on mental health in the ski resort industry. And thanks for the chance to ski the Rivah!

Just a blip on the radar. ⁣
 ⁣
I tweaked my knee while skiing back in Colorado over New Year’s. The good news is that it is super minor. It’s just a low-grade MCL sprain and bone edema (aka bone bruise). Honestly, in the world of knee tweaks, this is basically a best case scenario. It’s just going to take a little time off—merely weeks—and some TLC. ⁣
 ⁣
To be honest, I wasn’t sure if I’d even share it here. Sometimes it’s nice to keep some privacy to my life. But I wanted to share some thoughts because I’m proud of myself for applying a few lessons I’ve learned over the years:⁣
 ⁣
1) Multiple things can be true simultaneously, even when seemingly conflicting. ⁣
 ⁣
It sucks. It sucks because the circumstances and accident that caused it were honestly really lame. It sucks because I’m frustrated to be on the sidelines. ⁣
 ⁣
But I can also easily see the positives. It’s a minor issue and it will heal quickly. I’ll be back soon. This downtime gives me the silver lining of time at home to settle into routine, place my physical and mental health as top priority, and put time into other pursuits. ⁣
 ⁣
Both of these are true simultaneously. It can suck and it can be a net positive chock full of silver linings. Admitting and allowing it to suck helps me get to the positive side much faster and wholeheartedly. ⁣
 ⁣
2) Fuck the “stay hard” mentality I used to subscribe to. Ironically, I’m pretty sure the bone bruise portion of this is a flare-up from an old injury in 2018 I just gritted my teeth and skied through—just because I didn’t want people to think I was weak or soft and I thought my world would crumble if I lost the opportunities in front of me by taking time off. I’m proud of myself for taking my foot off the gas and taking care of this responsibly now.⁣
 ⁣
3) Listen when your body whispers so you don’t have to hear it scream. Granted, this is a loud whisper. But if I skied through it right now, I’d be putting my knee and body at risk for a more consequential injury. Again, I’m proud of myself for seeing the bigger picture and placing long-term health as a higher priority. ⁣
 ⁣
Anyhow, maybe some of that resonated with y’all. Much love. ✌️❤️

Okay, so because @officialwondermind was started by @selenagomez, does that mean we’re gonna hang out or what?!?! 
 
But on the real, a couple notes to expand on this headline: That gratitude to be alive probably seems like it boils down to near-death experiences. But here’s the thing: an accident in the mountains is just one of those experiences. I’m grateful to be alive from that, yes. But my gratitude for being alive goes deeper. When I’ve been in suicidal episodes, every single day is a near-death experience. And I know that’s true for the folks out there who have lived and are living that experience too. If you haven’t lived that experience, stop and think about the fact that multiple people in your life have been in that very same near-death experience I have. 
 
It’s why I share. It’s why I’m trying to create space for others to feel seen. Because we all need to know we’re less alone. Now, the gift and the opportunity to share myself and to create space for others to do the same is why I’m most grateful to be alive. 
 
Thanks to Wondermind for hitting me up to have a conversation. The link is in my bio for the whole Q&A that has a wide range of questions. I appreciate what they’re doing at @officialwondermind to elevate the conversation around mental health to be a mainstream norm. So @selenagomez, whether we end up hanging or not, thanks for what you’re doing and for creating space. I appreciate you doing so for me and I’ll pay it forward for others.

Wanna come join for the 2023 edition of one of my favorite weeks from last winter? I’m psyched to be heading back to Crested Butte for the Blister Summit. It’s an open invite to anyone and everyone and a guaranteed good time for a few reasons: 

- 4 days of on-snow ski and snowboard demos from @salomonfreeski and 30+ other brands (Translation: you get a chance to try all of next year’s skis before anyone else)
- Onhill meet-ups with professional athletes, Blister reviewers, product designers, & more (Translation: Let’s go ski Headwall and Fredo’s and Spellbound and Rambo together! Seriously, that’s my motivation to heal my MCL 100%.)
- Nightly drinks, appetizers, & panel sessions (Translation: Community building, meeting a bunch of friendly skiers, and quality conversations are the icing on the cake.)
- Last and most importantly, the skiing is SO good in CB. Crested Butte is one of my favorite spots and has been since I was a kid, especially when I was competing. Because when it’s good there, it’s as good as anywhere. I talked to three different friends this past week that said it’s firing down there and that they’re open wall-to-wall. If you know the magic of the North Face and Third Bowl, you know how rad that is. 
- And more.

It’s coming up February 12-16. Full details and sign up are in my story and bio and all over @blisterreview. I’ll be looking forward to going skiing with a bunch of y’all. 

@blisterreview @visitgcb @townofmtcb #blistersummit2023 #blistersummit

Back on skis! Patience and healing up properly seems to be paying off. I spent the past month and change doing all the little things that are really the big things—getting lots of sleep, putting my time in at the gym, and consistently making constructive daily decisions that add up over time.

During that time focused on rehab, I took a bit of a step back from time here on Instagram. I reluctantly admit that I found myself envious of everyone else out there skiing while I was on the sidelines. That part’s a simple truth: comparison is the thief of joy. But more than that, social media was just a time-suck. And frankly, it confirmed what I already knew: I’m happier and healthier the less time I spend on social media. Ironic, considering it’s part of my job, I know. But I’m figuring out a healthier relationship with it. 

Instead, I’ve been focusing my time during rehab on some deeper work—film projects, speaking, writing, some long-term visions I have for the future, and how to create real impact on cultural change around mental health. And that all feels really good. I’ll be excited to share those elements with y’all as time ticks along.

All that said, it was good to get back on skis in this manner: by sharing some laps with my dad. Ya know, the shit that really does matter. Because skiing with my old man, the most passionate skier I know who skis damn near every day, was a good reminder what skiing is really about. 

Cheers to the long ski season still ahead. Ski and enjoy, my friends.

3 years sober. 
F*ck, that’s a long time to go without a drink. And I ain’t gonna lie; I’m proud of myself for that fact. That part feels good to say “out loud” too. It feels good to own that. 

I’ve always been careful of how I share this element of my story because I don’t want my story to be written off as *just* a drinking problem. Truth is, drinking and sobriety are a relatively small part of my story, but this *is* an important part of my story. Sobriety is one of the ways I stopped holding myself back from pursuing my own path of personal growth—to which I will always be committed. 

In what at times feels like a culture with a heavy emphasis on drinking, it would have been a lot easier to get sober if I had known there were other folks in my sphere walking the same path. A few guys who actually really helped me in that regard were @semi_rad, @paddyroc, and @spencerharkins. 

I’ve been thinking a lot lately about how to make it easier for others. I think it at least starts with visibility in our community. So I’m trying to pay it forward now and open the door for others to know they have the option to choose however they want to live their life.

(Sidenote: My anniversary was actually almost a month ago. But I was busy doing some really meaningful-to-me stuff and I wanted to enjoy those experiences for what they were). 

Much love, my friends. ✌️

There’s a whole lot of new in this clip: not only new snow, but also new skis. The new-new @salomonfreeski QST 106 Echo is going to be an absolute weapon. As many of you have heard me say time and time again, the QST 106 has been my favorite ski for years, especially for touring. If I had to pick one pair of skis to do everything and ski for all of eternity it would be the QST 106 because of its versatility. But, alas, I’ve heard from many folks over the years that it’s a skosh heavy for an ideal touring ski. On big days last spring I finally conceded that a lighter weight ski would make a big difference. 

And now, here it is! The QST 106 Echo sheds weight while still being all that I love about the 106. I’m most fired up to use it for long days and big missions this spring. But in the meantime, it is indeed passing the powder skiing test. 🤙

Sure, it’s humbling to see @freeskiermagazine put the word “icon” next to my name, but seriously, I don’t care that this is about me. I don’t care that this is *just* an Insta story. I care that this is the ski culture and future I want to see. 

A few weeks ago, y’all poured out a lot of support when I shared the video about hitting three years of sobriety and some broader thoughts on such. Thank you all for the love. I’m sorry I don’t have the emotional bandwidth to reply to everyone personally. It was humbling to see the response, but this repost from @freeskiermagazine stood out for what it meant personally. I debated posting this back then, but circled back on it now—because each one of these conversations, posts, and mentions is adding up to something greater. 

As a kid, I worshipped @freeskiermagazine. I walked around the US Open of Freeskiing to get the who’s who of the sport to sign the 10th anniversary cover of the mag. Images of me, my writing, and my love for burritos have since landed in its pages. In years past, I’ve also gotten blackout drunk on their company credit card several times and danced on a roof while hammered drunk at their ski test.

As a kid or as a blackout drunk adult, I would have really benefited from seeing the conversation of sobriety and mental health elevated through them. And that’s why it stood out to me.

A year and a half ago, I said this in my @outsidemagazine essay, “We Need to Talk About Mental Health in the Mountains:”
“My whole life I’ve been celebrated for what I can do on a pair of skis. But what if our community celebrated people for taking care of their mental health in the same way? I believe that if we start honoring mental health like we honor getting rad in the mountains, lives will be saved. Much like my own journey, building a culture that supports mental health starts with talking about it.”

People have ever since asked me what that looks like. It looks like the ski culture, outdoor community culture, and the mountain town culture I’m intent on building. It looks like this. 

Thanks, @freeskiermagazine, @outsidemagazine, and each of you, for being a part of it.

It’s a truly special opportunity to get this massive crew of bright minds, nerdy, badass athletes, and driven dreamers all together in one place. However, a portion of that same crew botched the legibility of the body letters of “POW❄️” this bad. 😂😜

Over the past few days, @protectourwinters gathered our athlete alliance together to convene and strategize on how to move forward on meaningful, concrete, impactful climate action. Personally, I learned a myriad of new lessons on how to capitalize on and build upon the legislative win of the Inflation Reduction Act to shape the future of renewable energy in the U.S. and pursue paramount decarbonization goals. 

Between presentations and a visit to the National Renewable Energy Laboratory, we of course snuck in some group runs on the trail too. 

I always walk away from these gatherings with a full heart and the conviction that we can and will change the world. I say that with no hyperbole whatsoever. To feel that same empowerment and synchronize on this energy too, join #TeamPOW.

We skied such deep snow this winter that it resurrected @powdermagazine. 

Seriously though, @ming.t.poon put together a gallery with Powder from our two days with @codytownsend and @elysesaugstad that were truly deeper than the rest amidst this historic, apocalyptic winter. The last time I skied pow this deep was in 2020, which ultimately landed me on the penultimate cover of Powder before their hibernation. The last time I said that same sentence, Ming and I shot a cover of @backcountrymag last winter. So, on these couple days, I said the same thing—and lo and behold, Powder’s got them on their website as they rise from the ashes. 

The landscape of powder skiing, photography, magazines, and media outlets feels like it’s constantly in flux. But as someone with a very special place in my heart for Powder (and I interned there back in the day), this whole sequence made my heart smile. 

To see more of @ming.t.poon’s pics, the link is in @powdermagazine’s bio.

Little update here. This ski season’s been a little weird for me. A winter of historic porportions and limitless snow on one hand. On the other hand, it turns out my body has had some limits—maybe more than I’ve let on here on the interwebs. 

My knee (that I tweaked (low grade MCL) at the start of the new year) has ended up giving me a little more trouble. Admittedly, after some solid rehab back in Jan, I think I simply just skied too much in Feb and March and didn’t even out the balance of the scale with enough continued gym time, strength work, biking, and running.

It’s been good enough to still ski a little bit, but bad enough that it’s an unreliable partner in crime and impacting my body overall. I’ve had to turn down invites to trips and pass up opportunities, and I haven’t felt like I could rely on my knee to pursue all I wanted to this year. But all said and done, my knee let me have a lot of fun this winter. And for that I’m grateful. 

By taking a little time off in April, plus some added love, work, and self-control to balance out that scale, my knee’s doing a bit better. I’ve been getting it ready for a long spring using this fat snowpack for some good ol’ adventure skiing. I used it for one (really) big adventure so far, and it held up well enough. 

I’m optimistic for what my knee will allow with the long ski season left ahead, but I’m letting go of expectation and bull-headed ambition. I’m going to ski what my knee allows, and I’m going to enjoy it all for what it is. Nothing more, nothing less. Along the way, I’m going to keep telling myself that I’m proud I’m mature enough nowadays to listen to and take care of my body.

Badwater Basin to Mount Whitney. Going from the lowest point in the America’s (-282 feet below sea level) to the highest point in the Lower 48 (14,505 feet above sea level) totally under human power has been in my brain for the last six years. So I asked @easy_dog if he’d be game, and next thing I knew, we were freaking committed. 

Did we succeed in the goal? Did we almost die of heat stroke like @codytownsend? Did we ski worse than @alexhonnold? Did we do the whole dang thing with the goal of eating burritos on the summit being top priority? 

Well, the answers to all those questions ain’t the same. You’ll just have to wait until next fall for a full video.

6 years. May 10, 2017.
Today marks the anniversary of my rockfall accident on Mount Hood. Some people—combat veterans and survivors of all sorts—call this an “Alive Day.”

At first, I just wanted to get rid of the accident—from the timeline of my life, from my memory, from everything. I thought it would pass with one year. Nope, I was suicidal, depressed, and spiraling in PTSD at that point. Two years? Nope. That’s when I was learning that healing was going to take a lot longer than I ever could have realized. Three years? Still experiencing suicidal and depressive episodes. Five years? A younger me would have thought that would feel like a good, clean number to be able to move on. That was last year. Fuck, I even made a film about that spiral. Even now, six years later, I keep learning how deep it goes. Right now, I continue to explore the implications of the mind-body connection. I guess the point is: the importance has never lessened. It’s just morphed and evolved.

Last year, I went back to Mt. Hood for the first time since 2017. The volcano was socked in, hidden by a late May storm. I was there for my first “legitimate” paid speaking engagement, during a conference for terrain park and mountain operations professionals put on by Ski Area Management Magazine. I opened that talk the same way I now open many of my talks: with this photo and a simple message. Now, when I look at this photo, I don’t see the pain I felt. Now, I see the greatest, most important turning point in my life. 

Through a lot of therapy, renovating my entire life, and consistent intentionality and mindfulness, I’ve been able to change what this experience means to me. I’m glad that its importance has never lessened. Now, I’m grateful in equal parts that I have grown and healed so much, as well as have the opportunity to use my experience to help other people on my greater mission of cultural change on mental health.

On this day six years ago, I survived. Now, it feels more like my birthday than my actual birthday. Maybe that’s why people call it an Alive Day. Because on this day six years ago, I got a second chance at life itself. And I’m not wasting this second chance.

Thanks, y’all, for the love and support last week when I shared about my “Alive Day.” (Still not sure about that term, to be honest. I’ve just never known what else to call it).

Here’s how I celebrated when it passed last week. I skied in a Hawaiian shirt at @palisadestahoe and appreciated the feeling that I once had uncertainty my concussions would allow me to return to. I ran on a dry trail and listened to the birds sing. I snapped that selfie with my left arm that I’m fortunate to still have after the accident. I felt the warmth of the evening light on my face. I swam in Lake Tahoe. I deadlifted, which my back would not allow me to do with proper form for years afterwards, and now does. I worked on my new upcoming film (from Leadville last year; more about it soon) to continue my mission of driving cultural change on mental health. I meditated, journaled, and went to therapy. And I spent time with the people I love and care about. 

“Celebrate” is an intentional, deliberate word choice about my Alive Day, in each of those activities, and always. 

I met an old man in the grocery store a handful of years back who smiled at me when we made eye contact. I stopped and asked him how his day was going. As he hunched over, using the grocery cart as a walker, he responded with, “Well, I woke up on the right side of the grass again today,” and the flash of a toothy grin. We spoke for a few minutes. I think of him and what must be his catchphrase often. That’s what I was celebrating last week on my “Alive Day,” and every day that I’m fortunate enough to keep waking up on the right side of the grass. 

Peace out. I’m off to go celebrate again today. If you’re reading this, it means you’re fortunate enough to do the same today.✌️

Mahalo vibes. 🌴

Lately. 
Spring has to be my favorite season—although I’ve probably said that about every other one too. It’s the best time of the year for skiing up high. It has the novelty of just-melted-out trails down low. The sun is shining and I basically never wear real shoes all month when I’m not in ski boots or running shoes. It’s the best.

This May also brought with it the opportunity for me to see the Sierra through the lens of a beginner’s mind. But I guess every spring brings about the opportunity to see the newness of blooming flowers and returning birds and frogs croaking and the possibilities of the mountains. That beginner’s mind is what I love most—and what I intend to carry on from this spring.

I’ve received interview requests from The New York Times, HBO, Selena Gomez’s Wondermind (still waiting to hang with ya, @selenagomez 🤔). None of those can shake a stick at this one. This winter, @celestefrobin, a local high school senior in Truckee, reached out and asked if she could interview me for her senior project. 

Her senior project was how to help teenagers struggling with mental health and suicidal ideation. Fortunately for me, she also invited me to come watch her presentation. The audience was full of not only her classmates, but everyone in her school ranging from 6th-12th graders. Everyone was engaged, listening to her every wise, thoughtful word. They cared. 

In 2021, our roles were reversed. She was in the audience on the first year of the film tour and saw me present Ups & Downs. She shared with me that the experience helped her along her own mental health journey.

And now, less than two years later, that inspiration came full circle, with a return greater than I could have ever imagined. Watching her presentation, I was on the verge of tears, while simultaneously feeling my face hurt from smiling. I’m so proud. So inspired. So impressed and so full of hope for the future.

I love trail running so freaking much. The sport itself, the culture, the community, the energy, the MO, the vibe, the fashion, the simplicity, the camaraderie, the passion. All of it. 

This weekend, I participated in @brokenarrowskyrace at @palisadestahoe strictly as a spectator. I was originally signed up to run the 46K, but my knee issues from this winter told me to prioritize my focus on longer-term goals later this summer, so I pulled out. Injury is normally isolating, depressing, and lonely—all of which I’ve been experiencing. Instead, I did this. I ordered a vuvuzela off Amazon, donned a tutu, and made sure to cheer on friends and strangers alike for all three days of one of the greatest trail running festivals in America. 

If I could spend every weekend of my summer supporting friends (or strangers) pursuing their goals in this wonderful sport, I’d be a very happy man. Good news for me is that I’m doing so again next weekend too. 

📷 1:@ryanthrower of @runfreetrail, and on that note, I feel like this weekend epitomizes their motto of #TrailCulture
📷 2:@emily_tidwell_photo

Having a front row seat to witness an exceptional human pursue an exceptional dream is a sublime experience. 

A couple years ago, @easy_dog and I first crossed paths at the IMTUF 100. We missed the opportunity at that point to connect (my b 😬). We shared a start line that day. That was all, as he disappeared into the darkness to win the race while I simultaneously gritted through my slow, arduous first 100-miler. But this winter, we finally connected and learned how much more than a start line we shared then and the existential wavelength of living a deep life we share overall. We shared the Death Valley to Whitney (mis)adventure this spring. And we share an indomitable passion for burritos. 

On Saturday, Jeff chased his goal of a podium finish at @wser. He operated with an intensity and focus out of “The Last Dance” with Michael Jordan (and ran with his tongue out too). Simultaneously, he still possessed the wherewithal to smile, crack jokes, and thank those around him incessantly. All of it was done with a humble confidence that only a select few who are the greatest at their craft possess. He ended up finishing 9th overall, 8th among men. But more than any finish ranking, he shot his shot, truly *raced*, and pushed his limits. And the manner in which he did so was a compelling inspiration to behold. 

📷:@andrewfitts

Crewing and supporting my friends in their ultra goals is one of my greatest joys in life. That’s what I told @easy_dog when I offered to crew him for @wser. 

We all had call signs for the race. Checkmate was mine and yes, that’s me pictured with a clipboard (ahem, my namesake) and a radio (thanks for being on the other end, Radiohead (@davidkilgore) and Fluffer (@zachary_movement)) at times, because that’s how real this sh*t is. 

I also told Jeff that nothing was an overreach. He didn’t test that one, but it’s honest, too. The Waterboy (@drewtookapicture) and I had a running joke all day that if Jeff came into an aid station and had soiled his pants, that we were ready to take our shorts off on the spot to give him. Was that really even a joke though? No. 

This week has had me pondering why crewing is such a source of joy for me. Sure, being in service to others is a route to positive energy any time in life. Yes, the experience leads to a source and gathering of community—and we’re social creatures. But I think the greatest reason is that for one weekend, we get a miniscule taste of the level of commitment and heart it’s taken from our friend to get to that start line, pursue their audacious goals and dreams, and be brave enough to show up on race day and make it to that finish line no matter the circumstances. My eyes got watery seeing Jeff cross the finish line and hug his family afterwards—not because I know what it takes to run 100 miles, but because in that moment, I tasted a glimpse of what it took for him to run 100 miles. Thanks for welcoming me into the fold, Jeff and the Colt Crew (Colt Cult?). 

📷:@andrewfitts

These past couple weekends felt like closing the loop of the year-round connection I like to form with the mountains through skiing and running. Seeing @brokenarrowskyrace and @wser climb and traverse through the ridgelines, cliffs, chutes, nooks, and crannies I have been learning at @palisadestahoe over the last two winters was heart warming. This weekend, it is back to the skiing side of that loop. Have fun on the Alpine side, y’all, and I hope the Hawaiian shirts are out in force.

Plugging back in after the long holiday weekend. I spent it out in the Sawtooths with my brother and sister-in-law—backpacking, running, and yes, swimming in alpine lakes. But perhaps most importantly, unplugged. 

These quirky little reel audios are usually simply that. But per usual, Ryan Holiday drops some simple truth in this one. Some long walks did me good.

Here’s a selfie that I just thought was a good picture of me, at a gorgeous alpine lake, connecting with myself and the mountains, and having fun trail running. That’s it, that’s the caption. Not part of a hip photo dump, no reel, no CTA, no product to promote, nada más. Have a good weekend, y’all. #boobsweat

I’m so grateful to be here—to be running, experiencing these landscapes, feeling emotions, and seizing the opportunity of being alive. 

I’ve gone a little dark on social media as I’ve just had a lot going on—work, life, personal ups and downs, migraines—really just needing to take care of myself. 

My knee was more of a nuisance through the winter than I let on here on social media. I finally gave up on the cycle of skiing on it, hurting it some more, resting a week-ish to get it able to ski again, rinse, and repeat. After I hung up my skis at the end of May, my knee got better and my overall health and demeanor did too. It sucks when what we love most hurts us. But that’s life, ain’t it?

Rarely does an injury keep you from any other sport but let you run—especially a knee injury. The difference between skiing and running mechanically made sense why so, but even still. Despite the oddity, running’s what my knee has allowed. My doctor gave me a long leash and just insisted that I be honest with myself about symptoms. It hasn’t been a smooth build, a pretty Strava graph, or a spring/summer season of predictable training—or predictable navigation of life itself. I haven’t been sure I’d get to realize long runs in the alpine, run my race(s) this year, pursue my goals, build fitness, pace friends, or just feel fully like myself. But I’ve just kept listening what my body was in agreement with. And I’ve been sure to remember the real goal is to have fun. 

Last weekend, my knee generously gave me the green light. I grinded out about 50 miles and 18,000 feet of vertical gain between Saturday and Sunday. But it didn’t feel like training or forcing my body to perform or endure. It was just fun. I was with friends, new and old, in gorgeous mountains, and I was laughing, cracking jokes, jamming to @mileycyrus, and having deep meaningful conversations throughout. 

For now, for this week of training, for the rest of the summer and fall running season, for infinity and beyond, I’m just going to make sure I keep up that dynamic duo: listening to my body and having fun. 

📷:@sophia_steffens

Domino’s pizza visor + Cheetah print blouse + A LOT of vert = One heckuva buckle for @caseyroseut 

Casey and I first met when I was 16 and he was 14—truly back in the day—at big mountain ski competitions around the West. He was always an animal on skis. Still is. Somewhat full circle, in whatever you’d call this next chapter of life we’re in now, we’ve both gotten hooked on ultrarunning on a similar timeline. 

Last weekend epitomized the audacious goals he chooses. The Ouray 100 boasts 41,862 feet of vertical gain. Stop and read that again: *41,862 feet* of vert. It’s the most vert of any 100-miler in North America, at the least. (Anyone know of one in Europe or elsewhere with more vert that’s still 100 miles? i.e. not TDG)

I was lucky enough to pace him for the final chunk—some 29-ish miles and 13,000-ish of vert. He was a rockstar throughout. When he hit low patches, he just locked into gear and grinded through it. I cracked jokes, annoyed the heck out of him, and kept the train on the rails and in motion. Come the last section, he said he wanted to finish sub-40 hours. So he made up his mind he was going to climb 1,000 vert every 30 minutes, and simply put, he did the damn thing. It was seriously impressive, and I’ve seen and supported a lot of amazing athletes do amazing things. I’ll be drawing on this inspiration for a long time to come. Thanks for welcoming me into it and allowing me to share the magic of that experience with you, amigo. 

P.S. He finished not only sub-40, but in 38:41 and 9th overall.

Leadville 100—I’m running it back, baby. In less than a week’s time, on Saturday, I’m going to toe the line in the Race Across the Sky once again. But today, I present to you: the whitest video in ultrarunning. 

I’ve had a rocky year, so I’ve kept this a secret from most folks this whole year as I don’t like to spray unless I know I’m actually going to do what I say I will. But my body’s on board, I’m feeling mentally prepared, and more than anything, I’m just really excited and having fun. This week, I’ll plug back in more than I have been to share with y’all what the journey has been like to get back to the @ltraceseries LT100, what race week prep looks like, and of course, actually doing the dang thing.

2022 Leadville 100. Truth is, my road back to Leadville for 2023 started right here—mid-race last year. I’ve been told this is a moment when most people think to themselves, “well, son of a ***, I’m never doing this again!” But I thought to myself, “well, son of a ***, guess I gotta come back and do this again so I can apply these lessons!”

For what’s going on the better part of two years now, the @ltraceseries LT 100 has been a North star in my life. It’s brought me direction and purpose. I’ve found a lot of meaning within all of that—through building community, getting myself to be one day stronger than yesterday, through deepening my connection with the mountains and with myself, through continuing to show up.

Last year I also teamed up with @reelmotion to make a film out of skiing the peaks around the course, running the race itself, and the deeper mental health story within that Ups & Downs was just the beginning of. We’re still wrapping up the film and working on getting it funded. I’m really excited to share it with y’all whenever the time comes around because it is my next big step in my personal mission of creating cultural change around mental health. 

2022 also offered the opportunity to share my story in a multitude of ways. As a non-professional runner, I was pretty blown away by how far and wide it reached. I admittedly didn’t share all the media last year because sometimes the incessant self-promotion of Me-stagram is just a little much (ironic, this many years into doing it, I know). I really appreciate all the journalists and publications who connected with me though. What meant the most for me personally in all of it was that it felt like I was getting to pay forward the inspiration, camaraderie, and safe space for vulnerability and struggle that trail and ultrarunning has held for me—and continues to hold.

Anyhow, when the time came around last winter to decide on some 2023 goals, my first instinct was to go do something different, something new-to-me. But the more I thought and felt on it, the more my heart wanted to come back to Leadville. My heart wanted to come home. And that’s what it feels like now, in race week: home.
Just some trail thoughts. Hopefully @drewtookapicture is ready to give me his shorts if Saturday at @ltraceseries changes me.

My WHY. 
This is what will be in my heart tomorrow. This is what will get me to that finish line. I wrote this with the intention of sharing it as an Instagram caption, but I felt that it warranted sharing in the true human voice. 
—

Feeling connected to and supported by our community is essential for our health, both physically and mentally. Social connection may not be the first thing we think about when getting healthier, but it’s key to long-term health and well-being. 

One way to build community is to show up in places where support is already top of mind—like in the sport of running. #ReadySetCO

Leadville 100 Recap - Prep - (1/)

This is where the magic really happens to run 100 miles: in the spreadsheets.

Truth is, I wasn’t as fit this summer as I was a year ago. Starting 2023 with a knee injury that hampered winter, spring, and lingered into the summer sure didn’t help. I made it my goal to make it to both the start line and finish line healthy—any fitness on top of that was a success. 

So, in my preparation, I zeroed in on what I could do beyond just logging more miles. The biggest thing: race-day nutrition and fueling. Since April, I’d been training with an incessant focus on it. In my prior two 100’s, my race-day nutrition held me back from really utilizing the fitness I had built. This year, I made up my mind that wasn’t going to be the case. And I followed through.

I got myself dialed with the magic of spreadsheets and ziplocs. I had nutrition plans A, B, C, and D ready to enact. And I’d trained them all. 

It worked. I fueled and hydrated exactly to plan and felt the best I ever have in a 100, at least so long as the wheels stayed on… because after all, it’s still a 100-miler. But those stories are coming in another post.

Leadville 100 Recap - Starts with a smile - (2/)

“Remember to smile, it’s the biggest secret, smile and the world smiles with you.”

My dogg @easy_dog texted me that, among other words of support, at 3:29 AM on race morning as I bit into my pre-race breakfast burrito. That early morning text was the exact energy I needed 31 minutes before the start. I forgot the rest of what was on my mind, stressing me out—race details, crewing minutiae, gear forgotten at home, work emails—that limited my sleep the night before. None of that mattered any more. 

Smile. And the world smiles with you. 

That’s all I needed. I voice-texted him back as @margaret_t_spring and I jogged to the start line in my fashionably late, last-minute fashion, per usual. When Ken Chlouber pulled the trigger on the shotgun, I smiled my way down 6th Avenue, already feeling the positive energy loop of the world smiling right back. My cheeks hurt more severely and frequently than my quads all day long.

Leadville 100 Recap - Execution - (3/)

Call me crazy for learning to run ultras by racing only 100-milers and running any other ultra efforts on my own outside of a race environment. Sure, I know it would *make sense* to go learn some lessons by racing a shorter distance. But my motivation is pure and my heart is true for 100-milers. Maybe I’ll race shorter in the future, but here I am. 100% committed to 100. 

Executing an ultra is hard. Executing a 100-miler is even harder. There are so many variables at play. All the clichés ring true.

But like my preparation, I knew that my race-day execution was something I could focus on this year beyond just more miles and building fitness on a knee that’s held question marks most of the year. 

In my first 100, (excuse the following graphic description) I expelled demons out of every orifice in my body. Multiple times. In my second 100, I messed up my electrolyte balance and it wrecked my stomach, fueling, and hydration. Fortunately, the result was *just* incessant dry-heaving. I paced both poorly, blowing up and walking it in. I was determined to make my third 100 different. 

Frankly, I’m super proud of what I put together on race day. And it feels good to be honest about and own that with some pride. I breezed through aid stations, well-prepared and keeping things in rhythm, taking care of myself on course. I paced, fueled, and hydrated perfectly to plan and I executed to my fullest—at least for the first 50 miles. And then one of those old clichés resurfaced and rang true: 

“The only thing you can rely on is that something will go wrong in a 100. Solving what goes wrong is the real race.”

📹:@teagueholmes

Today was my favorite holiday of the year: FIRST SNOW!!!

As kids, my brother and I were only allowed to write on our mom’s calendar, hanging in the kitchen, one day every year: to mark the first snowfall of the season. We used to claim that square with exuberance, decorating it in snowflakes and ALL CAPS. After all these years, today was still, indeed, an ALL CAPS kind of day.

Leadville 100 Recap - Heat Exhaustion - (4/)

I didn’t sit down all day until about mile 55. I cracked. I finally gave in. I had the leans, dizzy, struggling to stay upright. Heat exhaustion got me. The high alpine exposure of the south side of Hope Pass and the apex of the sun’s arc won out. Icarus, realized. Perhaps I should have seen it sneak up on me, but despite my acclimatization, I passed the early signs off as the duration of my exertion at high altitude. 

A year ago, I gave myself rhabdo, landing myself in the ER for the bulk of the following day. Even after the cool flow of alpine creek water got me moving, the dehydration hole I’d dug was obvious. I was scared of giving myself rhabdo again and doing long-term damage to my kidneys.

But my crew forced me out of Twin Lakes at mile 62. That would be the last time I sat again until the finish line. When I expressed my fears of rhabdo, severe nausea, and concern if my body could rebound without consequences, @margaret_t_spring replied simply as she paced me and forced me to keep drinking and eating: “We don’t have time for that.” And we kept going. 

My body was still overheating. I plodded along shirtless past midnight. Ultra aid stations in the middle of the night are full of crazy-looking people—their sanity hanging on by threads. I was the most unhinged lunatic there.

Some eight hours after heat exhaustion took hold of me, I was finally moving swiftly and smoothly, I was peeing clear, my thermostat finally reset, and I had out-weathered the storm. 

We tend to perceive limits as finite. Heat exhaustion (or insert any “barrier” here) is a demarcation where we’re told to quit, to accept defeat, to respect the limits of our bodies. We’re told that backing off is what’s best for our health. I wish I’d had the wherewithal to dig even deeper earlier, but I persevered and told my body and self that none of this was a limit whatsoever. We are capable of so much more than damn near every human on this planet will ever begin to know.
I’m more of a Glacier Freeze guy tbh.

Month late and thousands of fallen leaves short, but fall sure was fun while it lasted. Aaaand I still wanted to make this funny video even if snow’s on the ground now.

It’s not often you get to ride a bike above 14,000 feet. It’s less often you get to do it on a road. And it’s even less often said road is closed. 

Amidst the travel and shows of the film tour, I’ve been carving out quality personal time when and where I can. On a weekend at home a couple-few weeks ago, we realized the road up Mount Blue Sky (formerly known as Mount Evans) was likely still clear—and also closed to cars for the season. So we rallied for one of the more memorable bike rides I’ve had. Fittingly, it was a classic day of Colorado blue sky. At the top, with the absence of shoe covers, we donned gas station shopping bags (shoutout to the nice lady who was down to give me 4 🙏 😂). One of those bags I also used to carry up a summit meal of Pringles before using it as a sock to stay warm on the descent. Nonetheless, we froze on the way down and laughed our way through the screaming barfies. But we made a memory. And that’s exactly what I’ve been trying to do with said intentional time. 

Anyhow, this was a fun one and I’ve been meaning to share it before ski season hits full swing. I’m en route home to Colorado now and psyched that @arapahoe_basin is open and spinning chairs.

16 shows, 10 states, 2 provinces, 2 countries, 6.5 different films (you’ll see what that 1/2 means in due time), thousands of skiers, and probably about the same thousands of miles. Year 3 of the Quality Ski Time Film Tour is in the books. 

I let it soak in over the past couple weeks and decompressed from such a wild season. 

Ultimately, all of this is about gathering, fostering, and celebrating the community of skiing. Ski films and in-person events are the vehicle. When @salomonfreeski and I started this whole shindig with that idea, I had no idea what it would turn into. 

My favorite moments from this year are the one-on-one conversations I get to have with skiers and the energy cycle that we create with the crowd at these shows. 

Most folks see me as a pro skier signing posters—and if you’ve been to a show, the MC on the mic. But to peel back the curtain a little more, behind the scenes I’m also producing the tour in lockstep with @salomonfreeski. Behind each show is months of planning and work. It’s been special to see all that work grow and blossom. 

And if you’ve been to a show, you know what a broken record I sound like: thank you. Thank you for coming. Thank you for sharing your energy. Thank you for making the sport and community of skiing what it is. Thank you. 

Thank you to @salomonfreeski, all the filmmakers, all the athletes, all the employees behind the scenes, and to our tour partners and sponsors. 

Ski and enjoy, my friends.

Skiing has brought me to some really unique corners of the globe and awe-inspiring mountains. But through the Quality Ski Time Film Tour, I’ve gotten to visit and see a lot of places right here in North America I might not have otherwise. I’ve gained an appreciation for cities, seen friends in their new homes, and developed a passion for road running—largely as a result of the past few years of this tour. And for all those reasons and a myriad more places than just these photos, I am super grateful. 

• Got to go full tourist in Yellowstone with @frankeltaylorchef. 
• PNW rainforest romp with @stephen_ettinger impressively close to downtown Seattle. 
• Seattle is one of my fave cities and one of my faves to run in. Got to do a downtown Seattle loop with @johnsonjoe & @bowersjohn. Went for a Puget Sound dip too. 
• San Francisco sunrise run with @zabie_e in the presidio. 
• Further and further enthralled by Vermont via a run with @tay.zehren and Trona in the first snowfall of the season in Burlington. 
• @mellawrence29 showing me her local trails in Bend. 
• My first time in Calgary and I loved it. 
• Seriously, Calgary has such cool parks, architecture, art, and more. 
• Boston is right up there for fave running cities and I copped a “wicked smaht” shirt from a street vendor mid-run. 
• No, really, @frankeltaylorchef and I went FULL tourist in Yellowstone.

A few years back, I listened to an interview with @selema, the quintessential voice of action sports. It was all-time and a must listen. (Seriously, go back and give it a listen with @richroll). But one specific nugget in there was how his broadcasting career started: by taking an opportunity to MC a skate comp and talk on the mic (if I remember correctly). 

That was right when @salomonfreeski and I were starting the Quality Ski Time Film Tour. So I said f*ck it, I’m going to MC this thing and learn something. If you’ve been to a show over the past three years of the tour, then you probably noticed: I have fun on the mic. 

Each show has its own distinct personality, identity, vibe, and energy. Nowhere and in no way is that more apparent than when I stand on stage alone and get to feel, see, and hear hundreds of humans. 

Fittingly in some ways, public speaking is one of my other careers that I don’t talk about on here as much. Much of that is very serious—usually about mental health advocacy and suicide prevention. It’s quite the opposite in many ways to stoking out a crowd to yell at powder skiing and cliff hucks. But I’ve learned a lot from MC-ing: how to read the crowd, improv when necessary, land a punch line, input a dose of energy. 

Like I said, I have fun with it. I don’t know that any of this will snowball even a fraction like it has for @selema. But I do know whatever it snowballs into will be fun. 

📷: @bowersjohn
